docs.text:
The 
storage1
 command-line interface 
(CLI)
 allows to use most features of the 
Google storage
 service from the comfort of your terminal.


By default all output is printed to standard out, but flags can be set to direct it into a file independent of your shell's
capabilities. Errors will be printed to standard error, and cause the program's exit code to be non-zero.


If data-structures are requested, these will be returned as pretty-printed JSON, to be useful as input to other tools.


Everything else about the 
storage
 API can be found at the

official documentation site
.


Installation and Source Code


Install the command-line interface with cargo using:


cargo install google-storage1-cli




Find the source code 
on github
.

  storage1 --help

Configuration:
  [--scope 
url
]...
            Specify the authentication a method should be executed in. Each scope
            requires the user to grant this application permission to use it.
            If unset, it defaults to the shortest scope url for a particular method.
  --config-dir 
folder

            A directory into which we will store our persistent data. Defaults to
            a user-writable directory that we will create during the first invocation.
            [default: ~/.google-service-cli]
  --debug
            Output all server communication to standard error. `tx` and `rx` are placed
            into the same stream.
  --debug-auth
            Output all communication related to authentication to standard error. `tx`
            and `rx` are placed into the same stream.





Configuration


The program will store all persistent data in the 
~/.google-service-cli
 directory in 
JSON
 files prefixed with 
storage1-
.  You can change the directory used to store configuration with the 
--config-dir
 flag on a per-invocation basis.


More information about the various kinds of persistent data are given in the following paragraphs.


Authentication


Most APIs require a user to authenticate any request. If this is the case, the 
scope
 determines the 
set of permissions granted. The granularity of these is usually no more than 
read-only
 or 
full-access
.


If not set, the system will automatically select the smallest feasible scope, e.g. when invoking a
method that is read-only, it will ask only for a read-only scope. 
You may use the 
--scope
 flag to specify a scope directly. 
All applicable scopes are documented in the respective method's CLI documentation.


The first time a scope is used, the user is asked for permission. Follow the instructions given 
by the CLI to grant permissions, or to decline.


If a scope was authenticated by the user, the respective information will be stored as 
JSON
 in the configuration
directory, e.g. 
~/.google-service-cli/storage1-token-
scope-hash
.json
. No manual management of these tokens
is necessary.


To revoke granted authentication, please refer to the 
official documentation
.


Application Secrets


In order to allow any application to use Google services, it will need to be registered using the 

Google Developer Console
. APIs the application may use are then enabled for it
one by one. Most APIs can be used for free and have a daily quota.


To allow more comfortable usage of the CLI without forcing anyone to register an own application, the CLI
comes with a default application secret that is configured accordingly. This also means that heavy usage
all around the world may deplete the daily quota.


You can workaround this limitation by putting your own secrets file at this location: 

~/.google-service-cli/storage1-secret.json
, assuming that the required 
storage
 API 
was enabled for it. Such a secret file can be downloaded in the 
Google Developer Console
 at 

APIs 
 auth -
 Credentials -
 Download JSON
 and used as is.


Learn more about how to setup Google projects and enable APIs using the 
official documentation
.


Debugging


Even though the CLI does its best to provide usable error messages, sometimes it might be desirable to know
what exactly led to a particular issue. This is done by allowing all client-server communication to be 
output to standard error 
as-is
.


The 
--debug
 flag will print all client-server communication to standard error, whereas the 
--debug-auth
 flag
will cause all communication related to authentication to standard error.
If the 
--debug
 flag is set, error-results will be debug-printed, possibly yielding more information about the 
issue at hand.


You may consider redirecting standard error into a file for ease of use, e.g. 
storage1 --debug 
resource
 
method
 [options] 2
debug.txt
.

Permanently deletes the ACL entry for the specified entity on the specified bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 bucket-access-controls delete ...


Required Scalar Arguments




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.






entity
 
(string)


The entity holding the permission. Can be user-userId, user-emailAddress, group-groupId, group-emailAddress, allUsers, or allAuthenticatedUsers.








Optional Method Properties


You may set the following properties to further configure the call. Please note that 
-p
 is followed by one 
or more key-value-pairs, and is called like this 
-p k1=v1 k2=v2
 even though the listing below repeats the

-p
 for completeness.




-p user-project=string


The project to be billed for this request. Required for Requester Pays buckets.








Optional General Properties


The following properties can configure any call, and are not specific to this method.






-p alt=string




Data format for the response.








-p fields=string




Selector specifying which fields to include in a partial response.








-p key=string




API key. Your API key identifies your project and provides you with API access, quota, and reports. Required unless you provide an OAuth 2.0 token.








-p oauth-token=string




OAuth 2.0 token for the current user.








-p pretty-print=boolean




Returns response with indentations and line breaks.

Available to use for quota purposes for server-side applications. Can be any arbitrary string assigned to a user, but should not exceed 40 characters. Overrides userIp if both are provided.

docs.text:
Creates a new ACL entry on the specified bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 bucket-access-controls insert ...


Required Scalar Argument




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


BucketAccessControl:
  bucket: string
  domain: string
  email: string
  entity: string
  entity-id: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  project-team:
    project-number: string
    team: string
  role: string
  self-link: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=eirmod


The name of the bucket.






domain=sit


The domain associated with the entity, if any.






email=stet


The email address associated with the entity, if any.






entity=sed


The entity holding the permission, in one of the following forms: 


user-userId 


user-email 


group-groupId 


group-email 


domain-domain 


project-team-projectId 


allUsers 


allAuthenticatedUsers Examples: 


The user liz@example.com would be user-liz@example.com. 


The group example@googlegroups.com would be group-example@googlegroups.com. 


To refer to all members of the Google Apps for Business domain example.com, the entity would be domain-example.com.










entity-id=et


The ID for the entity, if any.






etag=dolores


HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the access-control entry.






id=kasd


The ID of the access-control entry.






kind=accusam


The kind of item this is. For bucket access control entries, this is always storage#bucketAccessControl.






project-team    project-number=takimata


The project number.








team=justo




The team.








..    role=amet.




The access permission for the entity.






self-link=erat


The link to this access-control entry.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in

Creates a new bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.read_write




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 buckets insert ...


Required Scalar Argument




project
 
(string)


A valid API project identifier.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Bucket:
  billing:
    requester-pays: boolean
  encryption:
    default-kms-key-name: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  labels: { string: string }
  location: string
  logging:
    log-bucket: string
    log-object-prefix: string
  metageneration: string
  name: string
  owner:
    entity: string
    entity-id: string
  project-number: string
  self-link: string
  storage-class: string
  time-created: string
  updated: string
  versioning:
    enabled: boolean
  website:
    main-page-suffix: string
    not-found-page: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.






-r .billing    requester-pays=true




When set to true, bucket is requester pays.








..encryption    default-kms-key-name=eirmod




No description provided.








..    etag=elitr




HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the bucket.






id=amet


The ID of the bucket. For buckets, the id and name properities are the same.






kind=no


The kind of item this is. For buckets, this is always storage#bucket.






labels=key=labore


User-provided labels, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key






location=eirmod


The location of the bucket. Object data for objects in the bucket resides in physical storage within this region. Defaults to US. See the developer
s guide for the authoritative list.






logging    log-bucket=dolore


The destination bucket where the current bucket
s logs should be placed.








log-object-prefix=invidunt




A prefix for log object names.








..    metageneration=aliquyam




The metadata generation of this bucket.






name=accusam


The name of the bucket.






owner    entity=lorem


The entity, in the form project-owner-projectId.








entity-id=sea




The ID for the entity.








..    project-number=et




The project number of the project the bucket belongs to.






self-link=duo


The URI of this bucket.






storage-class=et


The bucket
s default storage class, used whenever no storageClass is specified for a newly-created object. This defines how objects in the bucket are stored and determines the SLA and the cost of storage. Values include MULTI_REGIONAL, REGIONAL, STANDARD, NEARLINE, COLDLINE, and DURABLE_REDUCED_AVAILABILITY. If this value is not specified when the bucket is created, it will default to STANDARD. For more information, see storage classes.






time-created=eirmod


The creation time of the bucket in RFC 3339 format.






updated=sanctus


The modification time of the bucket in RFC 3339 format.








versioning    enabled=true




While set to true, versioning is fully enabled for this bucket.








..website    main-page-suffix=amet




If the requested object path is missing, the service will ensure the path has a trailing 
/
, append this suffix, and attempt to retrieve the resulting object. This allows the creation of index.html objects to represent directory pages.






not-found-page=et


If the requested object path is missing, and any mainPageSuffix object is missing, if applicable, the service will return the named object from this bucket as the content for a 404 Not Found result.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Updates a bucket. Changes to the bucket will be readable immediately after writing, but configuration changes may take time to propagate. This method supports patch semantics.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:

If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 buckets patch ...


Required Scalar Argument




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Bucket:
  billing:
    requester-pays: boolean
  encryption:
    default-kms-key-name: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  labels: { string: string }
  location: string
  logging:
    log-bucket: string
    log-object-prefix: string
  metageneration: string
  name: string
  owner:
    entity: string
    entity-id: string
  project-number: string
  self-link: string
  storage-class: string
  time-created: string
  updated: string
  versioning:
    enabled: boolean
  website:
    main-page-suffix: string
    not-found-page: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.

HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the bucket.






id=sed


The ID of the bucket. For buckets, the id and name properities are the same.






kind=dolor


The kind of item this is. For buckets, this is always storage#bucket.






labels=key=dolor


User-provided labels, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key






location=dolor


The location of the bucket. Object data for objects in the bucket resides in physical storage within this region. Defaults to US. See the developer
s guide for the authoritative list.






logging    log-bucket=et


The destination bucket where the current bucket
s logs should be placed.








log-object-prefix=consetetur




A prefix for log object names.








..    metageneration=amet.




The metadata generation of this bucket.






name=voluptua.


The name of the bucket.






owner    entity=lorem


The entity, in the form project-owner-projectId.








entity-id=gubergren




The ID for the entity.








..    project-number=justo




The project number of the project the bucket belongs to.






self-link=sit


The URI of this bucket.






storage-class=vero


The bucket
s default storage class, used whenever no storageClass is specified for a newly-created object. This defines how objects in the bucket are stored and determines the SLA and the cost of storage. Values include MULTI_REGIONAL, REGIONAL, STANDARD, NEARLINE, COLDLINE, and DURABLE_REDUCED_AVAILABILITY. If this value is not specified when the bucket is created, it will default to STANDARD. The creation time of the bucket in RFC 3339 format.






updated=rebum.


The modification time of the bucket in RFC 3339 format.








versioning    enabled=true




While set to true, versioning is fully enabled for this bucket.








..website    main-page-suffix=sadipscing




If the requested object path is missing, the service will ensure the path has a trailing 
/
, append this suffix, and attempt to retrieve the resulting object. This allows the creation of index.html objects to represent directory pages.






not-found-page=vero

..

Updates a bucket. Changes to the bucket will be readable immediately after writing, but configuration changes may take time to propagate.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform

If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 buckets update ...


Required Scalar Argument




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Bucket:
  billing:
    requester-pays: boolean
  encryption:
    default-kms-key-name: string
  etag: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  labels: { string: string }
  location: string
  logging:
    log-bucket: string
    log-object-prefix: string
  metageneration: string
  name: string
  owner:
    entity: string
    entity-id: string
  project-number: string
  self-link: string
  storage-class: string
  time-created: string
  updated: string
  versioning:
    enabled: boolean
  website:
    main-page-suffix: string
    not-found-page: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.

HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the bucket.

The ID of the bucket. For buckets, the id and name properities are the same.

The kind of item this is. For buckets, this is always storage#bucket.






labels=key=clita


User-provided labels, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key

The location of the bucket. Object data for objects in the bucket resides in physical storage within this region. Defaults to US. See the developer
s guide for the authoritative list.






logging    log-bucket=takimata


The destination bucket where the current bucket
s logs should be placed.








log-object-prefix=nonumy




A prefix for log object names.








..    metageneration=kasd




The metadata generation of this bucket.






name=sanctus


The name of the bucket.






owner    entity=takimata


The entity, in the form project-owner-projectId.








entity-id=at




The ID for the entity.








..    project-number=labore




The project number of the project the bucket belongs to.

The URI of this bucket.

The bucket
s default storage class, used whenever no storageClass is specified for a newly-created object. This defines how objects in the bucket are stored and determines the SLA and the cost of storage. updated=rebum.


The modification time of the bucket in RFC 3339 format.

While set to true, versioning is fully enabled for this bucket.

If the requested object path is missing, the service will ensure the path has a trailing 
/

Creates a new default object ACL entry on the specified bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 default-object-access-controls insert ...


Required Scalar Argument




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


ObjectAccessControl:
  bucket: string
  domain: string
  email: string
  entity: string
  entity-id: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  object: string
  project-team:
    project-number: string
    team: string
  role: string
  self-link: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=tempor


The name of the bucket.






domain=sea


The domain associated with the entity, if any.






email=labore


The email address associated with the entity, if any.






entity=ipsum


The entity holding the permission, in one of the following forms: 


user-userId 


user-email 


group-groupId 


group-email 


domain-domain 


project-team-projectId 


allUsers 


allAuthenticatedUsers Examples: 


The user liz@example.com would be user-liz@example.com. 


The group example@googlegroups.com would be group-example@googlegroups.com. 


To refer to all members of the Google Apps for Business domain example.com, the entity would be domain-example.com.










entity-id=aliquyam


The ID for the entity, if any.






etag=dolores


HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the access-control entry.






generation=sit


The content generation of the object, if applied to an object.






id=diam


The ID of the access-control entry.






kind=ut


The kind of item this is. For object access control entries, this is always storage#objectAccessControl.






object=justo


The name of the object, if applied to an object.






project-team    project-number=est


The project number.








team=amet




The team.








..    role=accusam




The access permission for the entity.






self-link=clita


The link to this access-control entry.

The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the

You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Updates a default object ACL entry on the specified bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 default-object-access-controls update ...


Required Scalar Arguments




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.






entity
 
(string)


The entity holding the permission. Can be user-userId, user-emailAddress, group-groupId, group-emailAddress, allUsers, or allAuthenticatedUsers.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


ObjectAccessControl:
  bucket: string
  domain: string
  email: string
  entity: string
  entity-id: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  object: string
  project-team:
    project-number: string
    team: string
  role: string
  self-link: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=et


The name of the bucket.






domain=dolor


The domain associated with the entity, if any.






email=diam


The email address associated with the entity, if any.






entity=kasd


The entity holding the permission, in one of the following forms: 


user-userId 


user-email 


group-groupId 


group-email 


domain-domain 


project-team-projectId 


allUsers 


allAuthenticatedUsers Examples: 


The user liz@example.com would be user-liz@example.com. 


The group example@googlegroups.com would be group-example@googlegroups.com. 


To refer to all members of the Google Apps for Business domain example.com, the entity would be domain-example.com.










entity-id=invidunt


The ID for the entity, if any.






etag=rebum.


HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the access-control entry.






generation=lorem


The content generation of the object, if applied to an object.






id=clita


The ID of the access-control entry.






kind=invidunt


The kind of item this is. For object access control entries, this is always storage#objectAccessControl.






object=eirmod


The name of the object, if applied to an object.






project-team    project-number=at


The project number.








team=consetetur




The team.








..    role=et




The access permission for the entity.






self-link=sed


The link to this access-control entry.

The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the

.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.

...

(string)

(string)

Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


ObjectAccessControl:
  bucket: string
  domain: string
  email: string
  entity: string
  entity-id: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  object: string
  project-team:
    project-number: string
    team: string
  role: string
  self-link: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=ut


The name of the bucket.






domain=amet.


The domain associated with the entity, if any.






email=ipsum


The email address associated with the entity, if any.






entity=ut


The entity holding the permission, in one of the following forms: 


user-userId 


user-email 


group-groupId 


group-email 


domain-domain 


project-team-projectId 


allUsers 


allAuthenticatedUsers Examples: 


The user liz@example.com would be user-liz@example.com. 


The group example@googlegroups.com would be group-example@googlegroups.com. 


To refer to all members of the Google Apps for Business domain example.com, the entity would be domain-example.com.










entity-id=dolor


The ID for the entity, if any.






etag=sea


HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the access-control entry.






generation=ut


The content generation of the object, if applied to an object.






id=eirmod


The ID of the access-control entry.






kind=sanctus


The kind of item this is. For object access control entries, this is always storage#objectAccessControl.






object=voluptua.


The name of the object, if applied to an object.






project-team    project-number=dolor


The project number.








team=et




The team.








..    role=et




The access permission for the entity.






self-link=vero


The link to this access-control entry.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.

-r f.s.o

The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.

-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Updates an ACL entry on the specified object. This method supports patch semantics.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 object-access-controls patch ...


Required Scalar Arguments




bucket
 
(string)


Name of a bucket.






object
 
(string)


Name of the object. For information about how to URL encode object names to be path safe, see Encoding URI Path Parts.






entity
 
(string)


The entity holding the permission. Can be user-userId, user-emailAddress, group-groupId, group-emailAddress, allUsers, or allAuthenticatedUsers.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


ObjectAccessControl:
  bucket: string
  domain: string
  email: string
  entity: string
  entity-id: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  object: string
  project-team:
    project-number: string
    team: string
  role: string
  self-link: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=ut


The name of the bucket.






domain=sed


The domain associated with the entity, if any.






email=et


The email address associated with the entity, if any.






entity=ipsum


The entity holding the permission, in one of the following forms: 


user-userId 


user-email 


group-groupId 


group-email 


domain-domain 


project-team-projectId 


allUsers 


allAuthenticatedUsers Examples: 


The user liz@example.com would be user-liz@example.com. 


The group example@googlegroups.com would be group-example@googlegroups.com. 


To refer to all members of the Google Apps for Business domain example.com, the entity would be domain-example.com.










entity-id=justo


The ID for the entity, if any.






etag=dolore


HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the access-control entry.






generation=vero


The content generation of the object, if applied to an object.






id=dolor


The ID of the access-control entry.






kind=takimata


The kind of item this is. For object access control entries, this is always storage#objectAccessControl.






object=et


The name of the object, if applied to an object.






project-team    project-number=nonumy


The project number.








team=et




The team.








..    role=sed




The access permission for the entity.






self-link=no


The link to this access-control entry.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the

You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

Concatenates a list of existing objects into a new object in the same bucket.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.read_write




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 objects compose ...


Required Scalar Arguments




destination-bucket
 
(string)


Name of the bucket in which to store the new object.






destination-object
 
(string)


Name of the new object. For information about how to URL encode object names to be path safe, see Encoding URI Path Parts.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


ComposeRequest:
  destination:
    bucket: string
    cache-control: string
    component-count: integer
    content-disposition: string
    content-encoding: string
    content-language: string
    content-type: string
    crc32c: string
    customer-encryption:
      encryption-algorithm: string
      key-sha256: string
    etag: string
    generation: string
    id: string
    kind: string
    kms-key-name: string
    md5-hash: string
    media-link: string
    metadata: { string: string }
    metageneration: string
    name: string
    owner:
      entity: string
      entity-id: string
    self-link: string
    size: string
    storage-class: string
    time-created: string
    time-deleted: string
    time-storage-class-updated: string
    updated: string
  kind: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .destination    bucket=consetetur


The name of the bucket containing this object.






cache-control=dolor


Cache-Control directive for the object data. If omitted, and the object is accessible to all anonymous users, the default will be public, max-age=3600.






component-count=19


Number of underlying components that make up this object. Components are accumulated by compose operations.






content-disposition=elitr


Content-Disposition of the object data.






content-encoding=ea


Content-Encoding of the object data.






content-language=et


Content-Language of the object data.






content-type=stet


Content-Type of the object data. If an object is stored without a Content-Type, it is served as application/octet-stream.






crc32c=sed


CRC32c checksum, as described in RFC 4960, Appendix B; encoded using base64 in big-endian byte order. For more information about using the CRC32c checksum, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






customer-encryption    encryption-algorithm=dolor


The encryption algorithm.








key-sha256=sanctus




SHA256 hash value of the encryption key.








..    etag=dolore




HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the object.






generation=lorem


The content generation of this object. Used for object versioning.






id=consetetur


The ID of the object, including the bucket name, object name, and generation number.






kind=consetetur


The kind of item this is. For objects, this is always storage#object.






kms-key-name=eirmod


Cloud KMS Key used to encrypt this object, if the object is encrypted by such a key.






md5-hash=labore


MD5 hash of the data; encoded using base64. For more information about using the MD5 hash, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






media-link=gubergren


Media download link.






metadata=key=et


User-provided metadata, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key






metageneration=sadipscing


The version of the metadata for this object at this generation. Used for preconditions and for detecting changes in metadata. A metageneration number is only meaningful in the context of a particular generation of a particular object.






name=accusam


The name of the object. Required if not specified by URL parameter.






owner    entity=magna


The entity, in the form user-userId.








entity-id=lorem




The ID for the entity.








..    self-link=rebum.




The link to this object.






size=et


Content-Length of the data in bytes.






storage-class=clita


Storage class of the object.






time-created=eos


The creation time of the object in RFC 3339 format.






time-deleted=dolores


The deletion time of the object in RFC 3339 format. Will be returned if and only if this version of the object has been deleted.

Stores a new object and metadata.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.read_write




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 objects insert ...


Required Scalar Argument




bucket
 
(string)


Name of the bucket in which to store the new object. Overrides the provided object metadata
s bucket value, if any.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Object:
  bucket: string
  cache-control: string
  component-count: integer
  content-disposition: string
  content-encoding: string
  content-language: string
  content-type: string
  crc32c: string
  customer-encryption:
    encryption-algorithm: string
    key-sha256: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  kms-key-name: string
  md5-hash: string
  media-link: string
  metadata: { string: string }
  metageneration: string
  name: string
  owner:
    entity: string
    entity-id: string
  self-link: string
  size: string
  storage-class: string
  time-created: string
  time-deleted: string
  time-storage-class-updated: string
  updated: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=amet.


The name of the bucket containing this object.






cache-control=dolores


Cache-Control directive for the object data. If omitted, and the object is accessible to all anonymous users, the default will be public, max-age=3600.






component-count=32


Number of underlying components that make up this object. Components are accumulated by compose operations.






content-disposition=et


Content-Disposition of the object data.






content-encoding=sed


Content-Encoding of the object data.






content-language=et


Content-Language of the object data.






content-type=aliquyam


Content-Type of the object data. If an object is stored without a Content-Type, it is served as application/octet-stream.






crc32c=nonumy


CRC32c checksum, as described in RFC 4960, Appendix B; encoded using base64 in big-endian byte order. For more information about using the CRC32c checksum, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






customer-encryption    encryption-algorithm=sit


The encryption algorithm.








key-sha256=aliquyam




SHA256 hash value of the encryption key.








..    etag=sadipscing




HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the object.






generation=magna


The content generation of this object. Used for object versioning.






id=gubergren


The ID of the object, including the bucket name, object name, and generation number.






kind=sit


The kind of item this is. For objects, this is always storage#object.






kms-key-name=gubergren


Cloud KMS Key used to encrypt this object, if the object is encrypted by such a key.






md5-hash=sit


MD5 hash of the data; encoded using base64. For more information about using the MD5 hash, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






media-link=amet


Media download link.






metadata=key=eirmod


User-provided metadata, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key






metageneration=sanctus


The version of the metadata for this object at this generation. Used for preconditions and for detecting changes in metadata. A metageneration number is only meaningful in the context of a particular generation of a particular object.






name=lorem


The name of the object. Required if not specified by URL parameter.






owner    entity=amet.


The entity, in the form user-userId.








entity-id=diam




The ID for the entity.








..    self-link=eirmod




The link to this object.






size=sadipscing


Content-Length of the data in bytes.






storage-class=lorem


Storage class of the object.






time-created=sed


The creation time of the object in RFC 3339 format.






time-deleted=sit


The deletion time of the object in RFC 3339 format. Will be returned if and only if this version of the object has been deleted.






time-storage-class-updated=dolore


The time at which the object
s storage class was last changed. When the object is initially created, it will be set to timeCreated.






updated=et


The modification time of the object metadata in RFC 3339 format.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.




Required Upload Flags


This method supports the upload of data, which 
requires
 all of the following flags to be set:




-u (simple|resumable)


simple
 - Upload media all at once.


resumable
 - Upload media in a resumable fashion.






-f file


Path to file to upload. It must be seekable.








The following flag 
may
 be set: 




-m mime


the mime type, like 'application/octet-stream', which is the default








Optional Output Flags


The method's return value a JSON encoded structure, which will be written to standard output by default.




-o out


out
 specifies the 
destination
 to which to write the server's result to.
  It will be a JSON-encoded structure.
  The 
destination
 may be 
-
 to indicate standard output, or a filepath that is to contain the received bytes.
  If unset, it defaults to standard output.

-p
 is followed by one 
or more key-value-pairs, and is called like this 
-p k1=v1 k2=v2
 even though the listing below repeats the

-p
 for completeness.






-p if-generation-match=string




Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current generation matches the given value. Setting to 0 makes the operation succeed only if there are no live versions of the object.








-p projection=string




Set of properties to return. Defaults to noAcl, unless the object resource specifies the acl property, when it defaults to full.

The project to be billed for this request. Required for Requester Pays buckets.

Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current metageneration matches the given value.








-p content-encoding=string




If set, sets the contentEncoding property of the final object to this value. Setting this parameter is equivalent to setting the contentEncoding metadata property. This can be useful when uploading an object with uploadType=media to indicate the encoding of the content being uploaded.








-p predefined-acl=string




Apply a predefined set of access controls to this object.








-p name=string




Name of the object. Required when the object metadata is not otherwise provided. Overrides the object metadata
s name value, if any. For information about how to URL encode object names to be path safe, see Encoding URI Path Parts.

Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current metageneration does not match the given value.

Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current generation does not match the given value. If no live object exists, the precondition fails. Setting to 0 makes the operation succeed only if there is a live version of the object.








-p kms-key-name=string




Resource name of the Cloud KMS key, of the form projects/my-project/locations/global/keyRings/my-kr/cryptoKeys/my-key, that will be used to encrypt the object. Overrides the object metadata
s kms_key_name value, if any.

Updates an object
s metadata.


Scopes


You will need authorization for at least one of the following scopes to make a valid call:




https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform


https://www.googleapis.com/auth/devstorage.full_control




If unset, the scope for this method defaults to 
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform
.
You can set the scope for this method like this: 
storage1 --scope 
scope
 objects update ...


Required Scalar Arguments




bucket
 
(string)


Name of the bucket in which the object resides.






object
 
(string)


Name of the object. For information about how to URL encode object names to be path safe, see Encoding URI Path Parts.








Required Request Value


The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.


For example, a structure like this:


Object:
  bucket: string
  cache-control: string
  component-count: integer
  content-disposition: string
  content-encoding: string
  content-language: string
  content-type: string
  crc32c: string
  customer-encryption:
    encryption-algorithm: string
    key-sha256: string
  etag: string
  generation: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  kms-key-name: string
  md5-hash: string
  media-link: string
  metadata: { string: string }
  metageneration: string
  name: string
  owner:
    entity: string
    entity-id: string
  self-link: string
  size: string
  storage-class: string
  time-created: string
  time-deleted: string
  time-storage-class-updated: string
  updated: string





can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.




-r .    bucket=sanctus


The name of the bucket containing this object.






cache-control=takimata


Cache-Control directive for the object data. If omitted, and the object is accessible to all anonymous users, the default will be public, max-age=3600.






component-count=89


Number of underlying components that make up this object. Components are accumulated by compose operations.






content-disposition=ut


Content-Disposition of the object data.






content-encoding=sadipscing


Content-Encoding of the object data.






content-language=et


Content-Language of the object data.






content-type=clita


Content-Type of the object data. If an object is stored without a Content-Type, it is served as application/octet-stream.






crc32c=ipsum


CRC32c checksum, as described in RFC 4960, Appendix B; encoded using base64 in big-endian byte order. For more information about using the CRC32c checksum, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






customer-encryption    encryption-algorithm=dolor


The encryption algorithm.








key-sha256=elitr




SHA256 hash value of the encryption key.








..    etag=magna




HTTP 1.1 Entity tag for the object.






generation=aliquyam


The content generation of this object. Used for object versioning.






id=kasd


The ID of the object, including the bucket name, object name, and generation number.






kind=duo


The kind of item this is. For objects, this is always storage#object.






kms-key-name=et


Cloud KMS Key used to encrypt this object, if the object is encrypted by such a key.






md5-hash=sit


MD5 hash of the data; encoded using base64. For more information about using the MD5 hash, see Hashes and ETags: Best Practices.






media-link=eirmod


Media download link.






metadata=key=no


User-provided metadata, in key/value pairs.


the value will be associated with the given 
key






metageneration=lorem


The version of the metadata for this object at this generation. Used for preconditions and for detecting changes in metadata. A metageneration number is only meaningful in the context of a particular generation of a particular object.






name=sed


The name of the object. Required if not specified by URL parameter.






owner    entity=tempor


The entity, in the form user-userId.








entity-id=clita




The ID for the entity.








..    self-link=kasd




The link to this object.






size=elitr


Content-Length of the data in bytes.






storage-class=et


Storage class of the object.






time-created=vero


The creation time of the object in RFC 3339 format.






time-deleted=sadipscing


The deletion time of the object in RFC 3339 format. Will be returned if and only if this version of the object has been deleted.






time-storage-class-updated=sed


The time at which the object
s storage class was last changed. When the object is initially created, it will be set to timeCreated.






updated=vero


The modification time of the object metadata in RFC 3339 format.








About Cursors


The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:




The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the 
.
 character. Fields can be nested such as in 
-r f.s.o
 .


The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with 
.
, e.g. 
-r .s.s


You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify 
-r struct.sub_struct=bar
.


You can move the cursor one level up by using 
..
. Each additional 
.
 moves it up one additional level. E.g. 
...
 would go three levels up.

destination

  It will be a JSON-encoded structure.

 to indicate standard output, or a filepath that is to contain the received bytes.
  If unset, it defaults to standard output.

You may set the following properties to further configure the call. Please note that 
-p
 is followed by one 
or more key-value-pairs, and is called like this 
-p k1=v1 k2=v2
 even though the listing below repeats the

-p
 for completeness.






-p if-generation-not-match=string




Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current generation does not match the given value. If no live object exists, the precondition fails. Setting to 0 makes the operation succeed only if there is a live version of the object.








-p projection=string




Set of properties to return. Defaults to full.








-p if-generation-match=string




Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current generation matches the given value. Setting to 0 makes the operation succeed only if there are no live versions of the object.








-p predefined-acl=string




Apply a predefined set of access controls to this object.








-p if-metageneration-not-match=string




Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current metageneration does not match the given value.








-p generation=string




If present, selects a specific revision of this object (as opposed to the latest version, the default).








-p user-project=string




The project to be billed for this request. Required for Requester Pays buckets.








-p if-metageneration-match=string




Makes the operation conditional on whether the object
s current metageneration matches the given value.

The following properties can configure any call, and are not specific to this method.






-p alt=string




Data format for the response.

Selector specifying which fields to include in a partial response.

API key. Your API key identifies your project and provides you with API access, quota, and reports. Required unless you provide an OAuth 2.0 token.








-p oauth-token=string




OAuth 2.0 token for the current user.

Returns response with indentations and line breaks.

Available to use for quota purposes for server-side applications. Can be any arbitrary string assigned to a user, but should not exceed 40 characters. Overrides userIp if both are provided.








-p user-ip=string




IP address of the site where the request originates. Use this if you want to enforce per-user limits.

An opaque ID that identifies the resource being watched on this channel. Stable across different API versions.






resource-uri=aliquyam


A version-specific identifier for the watched resource.






token=sanctus


An arbitrary string delivered to the target address with each notification delivered over this channel. Optional.

The type of delivery mechanism used for this channel.

-p max-results=integer




Maximum number of items plus prefixes to return in a single page of responses. As duplicate prefixes are omitted, fewer total results may be returned than requested. The service will use this parameter or 1,000 items, whichever is smaller.

If true, lists all versions of an object as distinct results. The default is false. For more information, see Object Versioning.

Filter results to objects whose names begin with this prefix.

Returns results in a directory-like mode. items will contain only objects whose names, aside from the prefix, do not contain delimiter. docs.text:
The request value is a data-structure with various fields. Each field may be a simple scalar or another data-structure.
In the latter case it is advised to set the field-cursor to the data-structure's field to specify values more concisely.  For example, a structure like this:  Channel:
  address: string
  expiration: string
  id: string
  kind: string
  params: { string: string }
  payload: boolean
  resource-id: string
  resource-uri: string
  token: string
  type: string  can be set completely with the following arguments which are assumed to be executed in the given order. Note how the cursor position is adjusted to the respective structures, allowing simple field names to be used most of the time.   -r .    address=nonumy  The address where notifications are delivered for this channel.    expiration=magna  Date and time of notification channel expiration, expressed as a Unix timestamp, in milliseconds. Optional.    id=ea  A UUID or similar unique string that identifies this channel.    kind=sea  Identifies this as a notification channel used to watch for changes to a resource. Value: the fixed string  api#channel .    params=key=ipsum  Additional parameters controlling delivery channel behavior. Optional.  the value will be associated with the given  key    payload=true  A Boolean value to indicate whether payload is wanted. Optional.    resource-id=lorem  An opaque ID that identifies the resource being watched on this channel. Stable across different API versions.    resource-uri=aliquyam  A version-specific identifier for the watched resource.    token=sanctus  An arbitrary string delivered to the target address with each notification delivered over this channel. Optional.    type=et  The type of delivery mechanism used for this channel.
docs.title: Required Request Value

docs.text: The cursor position is key to comfortably set complex nested structures. The following rules apply:   The cursor position is always set relative to the current one, unless the field name starts with the  .  character. Fields can be nested such as in  -r f.s.o  .  The cursor position is set relative to the top-level structure if it starts with  . , e.g.  -r .s.s  You can also set nested fields without setting the cursor explicitly. For example, to set a value relative to the current cursor position, you would specify  -r struct.sub_struct=bar .  You can move the cursor one level up by using  .. . Each additional  .  moves it up one additional level. E.g.  ...  would go three levels up.
docs.title: About Cursors

docs.text:
The method's return value a JSON encoded structure, which will be written to standard output by default.   -o out  out  specifies the  destination  to which to write the server's result to.
  It will be a JSON-encoded structure.
  The  destination  may be  -  to indicate standard output, or a filepath that is to contain the received bytes.
  If unset, it defaults to standard output.

docs.text:
You may set the following properties to further configure the call. Please note that  -p  is followed by one 
or more key-value-pairs, and is called like this  -p k1=v1 k2=v2  even though the listing below repeats the -p  for completeness.    -p max-results=integer   Maximum number of items plus prefixes to return in a single page of responses. As duplicate prefixes are omitted, fewer total results may be returned than requested. The service will use this parameter or 1,000 items, whichever is smaller.     -p versions=boolean   If true, lists all versions of an object as distinct results. The default is false. For more information, see Object Versioning.     -p page-token=string   A previously-returned page token representing part of the larger set of results to view.     -p prefix=string   Filter results to objects whose names begin with this prefix.     -p user-project=string   The project to be billed for this request. Required for Requester Pays buckets.     -p delimiter=string   Returns results in a directory-like mode. items will contain only objects whose names, aside from the prefix, do not contain delimiter. Objects whose names, aside from the prefix, contain delimiter will have their name, truncated after the delimiter, returned in prefixes. Duplicate prefixes are omitted.     -p projection=string   Set of properties to return. Defaults to noAcl.
